habitat_description:
Northwest:
Breeding habitat consists of tall coniferous and mixed coniferous-deciduous forests from wet coastal environments at sea level to dry subalpine forest (Rohwer 1994, Hejl et al. 1995). It is most abundant in unlogged, old-growth forest, but also common in late successional stages (Mannan et al. 1983, Kessel and Kogut 1985, Wetmore et al. 1985, Hejl and Woods 1991, Tobalske et al. 1991). Over southern part of range in Idaho, Montana, Oregon, and Washington, forests suitable for breeding generally are characterized by =70% canopy coverage, tall conifers, high basal area, numerous conifer saplings, and dense deciduous undergrowth (Marzluff and Lyon 1983, Langelier and Garton 1986). This warbler is associated primarily with Douglas fir (Pseudotsuga menziesii) in w. Montana (Marzluff and Lyon 1983). In Washington, found in fir forests at high elevations in Cascades, but at sea level in extremely wet forests on western side of Vancouver Is., British Columbia (Rohwer 1994). In e. Cascades of Oregon (n = 15 nests), dominant tree species are grand fir (Abies grandis; 53.8 stems/ha ± 48.4 SD) and Douglas fir (13.0 stems/ha ± 9.6 SD); within old-growth stands, nest sites had higher volumes of grand fir and Douglas fir and more ground vegetation than random sites (Mannan et al. 1983)(quoted directly from Wright et al. 1998).

Southwest:
In the winter, Towsend's warbler prefers tall coniferous & mixed coniferous-deciduous forest (NatureServe 2004). Migrational habitat includes riparian thickets and high elevation aspen and spruce-fir in Arizona; junipers, pinon pines, and oaks on tops and sides of mesas in extreme western Oklahoma (Wright et al. 1998). Rare migrant through Utah; prefers coniferous forest habitat (Utah Conservation Data Center 2001). Uncommon transient statewide in Nevada; occurs in desert scrub, riparian, woodlands and montane forest areas (Alcorn 1988). Deciduous and coniferous forests and wooded urban areas in Colorado (Andrews and Righter 1992). Occurs to about 3,537 m in Colorado (Andrews and Righter 1992). In New Mexico as a spring and fall migrant, but is common and widespread (Ligon 1961). Occurs in cottonwoods and willows along the Cimarron River (Wright et al. 1998). Transient throughout Arizona (Phillips et al. 1964). In fall, found especially in mixed conifer forest, and uncommonly down to low elevations in Arizona; rare and irregular in winter in oak canyons and along lowland riparian stretches (Tucson Audubon Society 1999). In California, found in live oaks, mixed oak-coniferous forest, groves of conifers, chaparral, and stands of exotic trees in farms, ranches, suburban gardens, and parks (Dawson 1923, Small 1994)(quoted directly from Wright et al. 1998).
